<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHRYSLER ADS WILL TAKE AIM AT HONDA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chrysler Corp., trying to reverse a precipitous sales slide, unveiled Monday 
the next phase of its "Advantage: Chrysler" ad campaign with advertisements 
that take on the car maker deemed by many as the company setting the industry 
standard for automobiles -- Honda. 
</P>
<P>
The ads are based on an independent survey commissioned by Chrysler that show 
its smaller cars to be preferred overwhelmingly to similarly equipped Hondas by 
a random sample of 200 owners of General Motors and Ford autos considering 
buying imports. 
</P>
<P>
The car owners were polled last month in the Los Angeles area, where sales of 
imports are traditionally strong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
