<HEADLINE>
<P>
$310,000 'BOUNTY' PAID TO FIND NAZI 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WEST BERLIN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
West German Nazi-hunters paid $310,000 for information that led to the capture 
of a camp commandant charged with killing at least 5,000 Jews, the West German 
war crimes prosecutor said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
The record bounty was paid to an anonymous informer who led investigators to 
Argentina, where Josef Schwammberger had been living in hiding for three 
decades, Alfred Streim said after addressing the World Jewish Congress in West 
Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
Schwammberger, 78, was brought to West Germany from Argentina last week and 
faces trial in Stuttgart on charges of ordering executions, deportations and 
murdering Jews. 
</P>
<P>
The Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles helped make the case for his 
extradition from Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
