<P>
SELMA SUPT. QUITS, WILL DROP SUIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SELMA, Ala. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Selma's first black schools superintendent resigned Monday and said he would 
drop his $10-million racial discrimination suit against the city and the school 
board in return for a cash settlement. 
</P>
<P>
Norward Roussell cited the stress of the turmoil surrounding his case since the 
school board voted late last year to dismiss him. 
</P>
<P>
He said the settlement was "close to" what he would have received if his 
three-year, $69,500-a-year contract had been renewed, about $208,500. 
</P>
<P>
The vote by the white-controlled board not to renew Roussell's contract sparked 
protests by blacks, some of whom were arrested during demonstrations. 
</P>
<P>
The board said it voted to dismiss Roussell him because of his management 
style. 
</P>
