<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
NIGERIA SLASHES OIL PRODUCTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LAGOS, Nigeria 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nigeria announced a big cut in its oil output today in line with moves by other 
OPEC states to support prices, which have fallen by up to 25% this year. 
</P>
<P>
"The amount that Nigeria was supposed to be making in excess of its quota was 
140,000 barrels per day. 
</P>
<P>
This is the amount by which we intend to cut down," said Oil Minister Jubril 
Aminu. 
</P>
<P>
The 13 members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries decided at 
an emergency meeting in Geneva last week to cut output by 1.445 million barrels 
a day to try to mop up an oil surplus seen as responsible for the sharp fall in 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's output was estimated at 1.75 million barrels a day in April against 
an allocated quota of 1.611 million. 
</P>
<P>
With total group output 1.5 million to 2 million barrels a day above its 22 
million barrel-a-day ceiling, set last November, prices for the actively traded 
Brent oil crashed below $16 a barrel last month from as high as $20 in January. 
</P>
<P>
OPEC's target price for a basket of its crudes is $18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
